    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Father</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>The following is the solid content of the box, which I forgot to measure last week.</p>
<p>211<hi rend="superscript">.</hi>44 Cubic inches</p>
<p>Your affec son. | Leonard Darwin</p>
<p><hi rend="underline">Iron box of earth</hi>.</p>
<p>Measurement after being well dried before the fire. = 180<hi rend="superscript">.</hi>8 Cubic inches. This shews that it has diminished 10 per cent on the original earth, without taking into account internal shrinking, although cracks were visible on the surface.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="cdnotes">
            <note> 
<p>March. 29.1872.</p>
<p>Leonard</p>
<p>Earth dug out of ground &amp; thrown up in fortification   increase 〈of〉 above <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac></math></formula><hi rend="superscript">th</hi> of bulk.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p></note>
              </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by CD’s note.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2241.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Earthworms</hi></ref>, pp. 161–2, where he gave measurements of dried earth by weight rather than volume, CD concluded that the largest castings were produced on the poorest soils, indicating that worms had to swallow a greater amount of earth on poor land in order to obtain enough food.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">A further set of calculations, made by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Howard Darwin</ref> on the letter, estimates that the loss in volume of the dried earth is approximately <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></math></formula>.</note>
        </div>        
            
